## Three petty crimes in `src/petty.ts`

### 1. `describeCheckout` — Option Bag Junk Drawer (crime_00017, lines 10-19)

**What an agent gets wrong today:** `CheckoutOptions` lumps six unrelated dimensions — billing (`plan`, `currency`), routing (`region`), auth (`role`), runtime state (`status`, `retry`) — into one bag. An agent told to "add a `couponCode` field" has no signal that coupons belong with billing rather than next to `role`. A caller passing `{ retry: true }` while omitting `status` gets no compile-time warning that the omission matters here.

**Refactor:** name the shape this function actually consumes. Either tight inline destructure or a purpose-named type:

```ts
type CheckoutDescriptor = {
  plan: string;
  role: string;
  region: string;
  currency: string;
  status: string;
  retry: boolean;
};

export function describeCheckout(d: CheckoutDescriptor): string {
  return [d.plan, d.role, d.region, d.currency, d.status, String(d.retry)].join(":");
}
```

The win is the rename: `CheckoutDescriptor` says "this is the data needed to build a checkout description string," not "a generic envelope of checkout-adjacent properties." Future fields land in the type whose name actually fits.

### 2. `resolvePaymentResult` — Return Shape Roulette (crime_00018, lines 21-32)

**What an agent gets wrong today:** three branches return three different shapes (`{ ok, code, message }`, `{ url, permanent }`, `{ ok, value, cached }`) with **0% key overlap** between the error and redirect branches, and no declared return type. A caller writing `result.ok` after a redirect gets `undefined` — silently falsy. An agent extending this with a fourth branch will pick whichever shape they happen to read first, drifting further.

**Refactor:** make the variants explicit with a discriminated union:

```ts
type PaymentResult =
  | { kind: "error"; code?: string; message?: string }
  | { kind: "redirect"; url?: string; permanent: boolean }
  | { kind: "success"; value?: string; cached: boolean };

export function resolvePaymentResult(input: {
  error?: boolean; redirect?: boolean;
  code?: string; message?: string; url?: string; value?: string;
}): PaymentResult {
  if (input.error)    return { kind: "error",    code: input.code, message: input.message };
  if (input.redirect) return { kind: "redirect", url: input.url, permanent: false };
  return { kind: "success", value: input.value, cached: false };
}
```

`kind` forces callers to discriminate. The compiler now refuses `result.url` on an error result, and a future fifth branch must declare its own `kind`.

### 3. `canRunBilling` — Negative Flag Maze (crime_00019, line 35)

**What an agent gets wrong today:** `!disableBilling && !skipRetry` is a double negative. Asked to "also block when the tenant is in `readonly` mode," an agent is likely to bolt on `&& !readonly` and quietly invert the intent of a future caller that genuinely wants readonly billing. The parameter names already encode the wrong polarity — every reader has to mentally flip them.

**Refactor:** flip to positive flags at the boundary, name the predicate:

```ts
export function canRunBilling(
  flags: { billingEnabled: boolean; retriesEnabled: boolean }
): boolean {
  return flags.billingEnabled && flags.retriesEnabled;
}
```

If callers genuinely own `disableBilling`/`skipRetry` and you can't rename them, at minimum extract the predicate:

```ts
export function canRunBilling(disableBilling: boolean, skipRetry: boolean): boolean {
  const billingEnabled = !disableBilling;
  const retriesEnabled = !skipRetry;
  return billingEnabled && retriesEnabled;
}
```

The named locals turn "is this true when both are false?" into "is this true when both are enabled?" — which is the question a fourth condition should be added to.

---

**Common thread:** all three findings are about *implicit contracts*. The fix in each case is to name the thing — the input shape, the output variant, the boolean polarity — so the next edit has a place to land instead of a guess to make.
